Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Wolryche of Wenlock was born about 1368, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of Roger Wolryche and Margaret Upton. He had at least 2 sons with Margaret de Dudmaston."},"et":{"abt1368–":"umbes 1368–Surnud","1368–Male":"1368–Surnud","1376–1418":"1376–1418","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1368":"1368","1400":"1400","abt. 1400":"umbes 1400","abt1368":"umbes 1368","1376":"1376","1340":"1340","1418":"1418","of Dudmaston, Shrpsh., Engl.":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"abt1368–":"noin 1368–Kuollut","1368–Male":"1368–Kuollut","1376–1418":"1376–1418","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1368":"1368","1400":"1400","abt. 1400":"noin 1400","abt1368":"noin 1368","1376":"1376","1340":"1340","1418":"1418","of Dudmaston, Shrpsh., Engl.":"Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"abt1368–":"environ 1368–Décédé","1368–Male":"1368–Décédé","1376–1418":"1376–1418","1400–Male":"1400–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1340–Male":"1340–Décédé","–Female":"Décédée","1368":"1368","1400":"1400","abt. 1400":"environ 1400","abt1368":"environ 1368","1376":"1376","1340":"1340","1418":"1418","of Dudmaston, Shrpsh., Engl.":"Shropshir